Implement the private `do_levenshtein/3` function.

This is the inner dynamic-programming kernel of the Levenshtein distance
calculation. It is only ever called from `levenshtein/2` after that function has:

- split both strings into grapheme lists,
- swapped them so that `a_graphs` is the **longer** (or equal-length) list and
  `b_graphs` is the shorter one, and
- verified that both lists are non-empty.

`do_levenshtein/3` receives:

- `a_graphs` — the longer grapheme list (the "rows" of the DP matrix),
- `b_graphs` — the shorter grapheme list (the "columns"),
- `n` — the length of `b_graphs`.

It must return the Levenshtein (edit) distance between the two grapheme lists as a
non-negative integer, computed with an iterative two-row dynamic-programming scheme:

- Seed the "previous row" with the values `0, 1, 2, …, n` (the cost of turning an
  empty prefix of `a` into each prefix of `b`), stored as a tuple for O(1) indexing.
- For each character `a_char` of `a_graphs` at 1-based index `i`, build the next row
  from left to right. The leftmost cell of the new row is `i` (deleting `i`
  characters). For each character `b_char` of `b_graphs` at 1-based index `j`, compute
  the cell value as the minimum of:
  - `left + 1` (insertion, where `left` is the just-computed cell to the left),
  - `up + 1` (deletion, where `up` is `elem(prev_row, j)`),
  - `diag + cost` (substitution/match, where `diag` is `elem(prev_row, j - 1)` and
    `cost` is `0` when `a_char == b_char`, otherwise `1`).
- Carry each completed row forward as the new "previous row" (again as a tuple), and
  after processing every character of `a_graphs`, return the last element of the final
  row — `elem(final_row, n)`.

